-- PRESS DIGEST - Bulgaria - Nov 17
-- 
-- Mon Nov 17, 2014 03:01AM EST
-- None



SOFIA, Nov 17 (Reuters) - These are some of the main stories in Bulgarian newspapers on Monday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

-- Ten-year-old singer Krisia and pianists Hasan and Ibrahim, also 10, captivated both the audience and the jury in many of the countries which were allowed to give points to finish second at the Junior Eurovision contest in Malta. The Bulgarians won 147 points, 12 behind Italian winner Vincenzo Cantiello (Standart, 24 Chasa) -- A new western European investor has shown interest in the construction of the nuclear power plant at the Danube town of Belene, an energy expert Atanas Tasev said, adding that the government will make an official announcement in the coming days. The energy ministry officials said no one contacted them on the issue (Sega, Duma, Presa). -- Foreign Minister Daniel Mitov warned of risk of "import of terrorists" from Iraq and Syria, adding that Bulgaria will seek aid from the European Commission to handle the increasing flow of illegal immigrants (Standart, 24 Chasa). -- Bulgaria may complete delayed construction of its Maritsa motorway next August next year, Regional Minister Lilyana Pavlova said (Standart, Presa, Monitor, Capital daily, 24 Chasa). -- Interior Minister Veselin Vuchkov said that migrant pressure and a shortage of finds are the main issues his ministry should tackle in near (Trud, Standart, Sega, Monitor).